Incident.Summary: The driver is in possession of suspected Phencyclidine (PCP).

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: This stop was audibly and visually recorded using the Axon Digital Video Camera System installed in Maryland State Police Unit, U-4, as well as my Axon Body-Worn Camera. PHYSICAL EVIDENCE: One (1) Maryland State Police Chain of Custody Log (MSP Form 67) One (1) Maryland State Police Property Record (P-345916) Three (3) whole, and two (2) partial cigarettes, soaked in suspected Phencyclidine (PCP) NARRATIVE: On September 30, 2023, at approximately 0043 hours, I observed a gray 2016 Ford Taurus, bearing Maryland registration 6FM0288, traveling southbound on Main Street in the area of the Maryland State Police Prince Frederick Barrack, located at 210 Main Street, Prince Frederick, Calvert County, Maryland. I observed the vehicle did not have any taillights illuminated. I activated my emergency equipment and initiated a traffic stop on Calvert Towne Drive, just west of Main Street, Prince Frederick, Maryland. I approached the vehicle and made contact with the driver, Brian Keith Holland Jr (B/M, 01/17/1988), who was identified by his Maryland identification card. Holland was the sole occupant of the vehicle. While speaking with Holland, I detected a strong chemical odor emitting from the interior of the vehicle. Through my training, knowledge, experience, and prior narcotics investigations as a Maryland State Trooper, I suspected the strong chemical odor to be Phencyclidine (PCP). Holland appeared to be visibly nervous and lethargic. Hollands speech was slurred, and he had a blank, unfocused gaze. Through my training, knowledge, and experience, I believed Holland was under the influence. I requested Holland to exit the vehicle, at which time he complied. I requested Holland to exit the vehicle to perform the Standardized Field Sobriety Tests. As Holland was exiting the vehicle, I observed a partially broken, and soaking wet looking cigarette fall to the pavement. In plain view inside the vehicle, I observed additional soaking wet cigarettes on the floorboard, directly under the drivers seat where Holland was sitting. I immediately detained Holland in handcuffs and retrieved gloves and a plastic bag from my patrol vehicle. I conducted a search incident to arrest, and located the below listed CDS in Hollands vehicle: * Three (3) whole, and two (2) partial cigarettes, soaked in suspected Phencyclidine (PCP) The above listed CDS was identified through my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper. The above listed CDS is commonly referred to as a Dipper. A Dipper is a cigarette that is soaked in Phencyclidine (PCP), and then smoked/consumed. Phencyclidine is a Schedule II Controlled Dangerous Substance. At approximately 0057 hours, I read Holland his Miranda Rights. Holland verbally stated he understood his Miranda Rights, and verbally elected to speak with me. Holland stated he spilled Gatorade on his cigarettes, and the liquid soaked cigarettes was not PCP. After conducting a search of the vehicle, no Gatorade was observed or located. It should also be noted that the seats and floorboards throughout Hollands vehicle were dry, and there was no indication of any liquid spilling. The weather was clear, and it had not rained. I transported Holland to the Maryland State Police Prince Frederick Barrack to administer the Standardized Field Sobriety Tests. This was done for officer safety due to Holland potentially being under the influence of PCP. Once at the Barrack, I administered the Standardized Field Sobriety Tests with Holland. I did not find Holland to be driving under the influence of a controlled dangerous substance. I transported Holland to the Calvert County Detention Center for further processing. Holland was charged with the following: *1_1111* CR 5-601 (a)(1) Possession of CDS: Not Cannabis The CDS was packaged and processed in accordance with MSP policy and procedures. The CDS was logged on MSP Property Record (P-345916), and placed into the Barrack Property Room at approximately 0430 hours. Case closed by arrest. All events occurred in Calvert County, Maryland.
